{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"c0bc705d711c37dc2a0b8ac84255ef4adc75f5d61d85e7cedbbbebfc0df6aa20","slug":"pages.m12-summary-probability","location":"/pages/173-m12-summary-probability.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Summary (Probability)","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Shawn Wiggins","given":"Shawn","family":"Wiggins"},"name":"Shawn Wiggins","affiliations":["City College of San Francisco"],"id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true}},"affiliations":[{"id":"City College of San Francisco","name":"City College of San Francisco"}],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"173-m12-summary-probability.md","url":"/build/173-m12-summary-prob-9b71b84157bdcb09639a157a2321a4ed.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This summary provides a quick recap of the material you’ve learned in the probability unit. Please note that this summary does not provide complete coverage of the material, but just lists the main points. We therefore recommend that you use this summary only as a checklist or a review before going on to the next unit, or before an exam.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"rnTL8AkeH7"}],"key":"wL4Kce7y6r"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"General Remarks","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"xkleMOBypz"}],"identifier":"general-remarks","label":"General Remarks","html_id":"general-remarks","implicit":true,"key":"h8M7paeZEH"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Probability is a discipline by itself. In the context of the big picture of this course, probability is used to quantify the imperfection associated with drawing conclusions about the entire population based only on a random sample drawn from it.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"EK3ZDtY9k3"}],"key":"ciGTEMweph"}],"key":"ajk2TPGQ5t"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"We talk about the probability of an event, which is a statement about the outcome of a random experiment. In practice, each event corresponds to a subset of outcomes from the sample space.","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"Fku9QjgDy5"}],"key":"vYKDPFnzcU"}],"key":"OkFn9oAc3y"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The probability of an event can be as low as 0 (when the event is impossible) and as high as 1 (when the event is certain).","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"rU87blNRfQ"}],"key":"N4OTzXPkF4"}],"key":"hmqeV5iclc"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"In some cases, the only way to find the probability of an event of interest is by repeating the random experiment many times and using the relative frequency approach.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"PziKEQAE4b"}],"key":"ru1DKIjbiy"}],"key":"V4RNa71J5O"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"When all the possible outcomes of a random experiment are equally likely, the probability of an event is the fraction of outcomes which satisfy it.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"Yr5oUOVc18"}],"key":"FAOJiOq3qC"}],"key":"K7t8SvN76k"}],"key":"sRRZzgGto6"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Probability Principles","position":{"start":{"line":13,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"key":"N5MtaaFGcD"}],"identifier":"probability-principles","label":"Probability Principles","html_id":"probability-principles","implicit":true,"key":"q3eoQy6N9i"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Probability principles help us find the probability of events of certain types:","position":{"start":{"line":15,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"Fy2XBJCAJ5"}],"key":"Guww3v5Uv6"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Complement Rule","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"iBY5Smx7ak"}],"key":"FATkKd2KkY"},{"type":"text","value":", P(not A) = 1 - P(A), is especially useful for finding events of the type “at least one of ...”","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"j9Wpmarrp1"}],"key":"RZxFU0ZOMr"}],"key":"ijF3beczRn"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"To find the probability of ","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"c2zPRXdxzM"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"events of the type “A or B”","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"oTheYRr918"}],"key":"wpZF89Tp1n"},{"type":"text","value":"(interpreted as A occurs or B occurs or both), we use the General Addition Rule: P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B). In the special case when A and B are disjoint (cannot happen together; P(A and B) = 0) the Addition Rule reduces to: P(A and B) = P(A) + P(B).","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"p4UpMoawFV"}],"key":"YqkaF1YgzJ"}],"key":"tQCMFgAJiI"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"To find the probability of ","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"i6MeTBIqVY"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"events of the type “A and B”","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"WpFXVPJmty"}],"key":"Yq7y1imjnX"},{"type":"text","value":" (interpreted as both A and B occur), we use the General Multiplication Rule: P(A and B) = P(A) * P(B | A). In the special case when A and B are independent (the occurrence of one event has no effect on the probability of the other occurring; P(B | A) = P(B)) the Multiplication Rule reduces to: P(A and B) = P(A) * P(B).","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"o6xysDYeV3"}],"key":"QzQTVEdY96"}],"key":"VBTYi4Orcu"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"P(B | A), the conditional probability of event B occurring given that event A has occurred, can be viewed as a reduction of the sample space S to event A. The conditional probability, then, is the fraction of event A where B occurs as well, P(B | A) = P(A and B) / P(A).","position":{"start":{"line":20,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"key":"GWZD4ecAAJ"}],"key":"VzBR9tz14x"}],"key":"pnujKz9V2S"}],"key":"p5ei3ZYSiG"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Probability trees are a useful visual tool for displaying and manipulating probabilities of events which naturally happen in sequence (or in stages). It is particularly useful when we are given conditional probability in one direction P(B | A), and need to find the reverse conditional probability P(A | B).","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"N02KxBLmVS"}],"key":"tybMT3a0IX"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Random Variables","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"ycSd3l5Bdu"}],"identifier":"random-variables","label":"Random Variables","html_id":"random-variables","implicit":true,"key":"fwAYdwmdKl"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A random variable is a variable whose values are numerical results of a random experiment.","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"IOy4ysl7gU"}],"key":"hsawRTD8b4"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"sta